The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, July 03, 2004 				 Tax mopup swells 20% to touch Rs 17297 cr
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, July 2: The Centres gross tax collections rose 20 per cent to touch the Rs 17,297-crore mark during the first two months of the current fiscal compared with the same period of the previous year.																								However, the growth in tax collections was negated by the higher expenditure during this period and the fiscal deficit rose 14 per cent to Rs 38,982 crore.																								One positive feature is that income-tax collection rose 46 per cent to Rs 5,676 crore till May from Rs 3,875 crore in the same period of the previous year. 																								On the indirect tax front, the reduction in peak rates of custom duties to 20 per cent on a number of high-value items in January resulted in decline in customs collections. 																								Customs duties witnessed 5 per cent fall to Rs 7,162 crore during April-May from Rs 7,545 crore in the same period of the previous financial year.																								Excise mop-up swelled over 16 per cent to Rs 6,270 crore in the first two months of this fiscal from Rs 5,385 crore in the same period of the previous financial year. Collection of other taxes rose 60 per cent to Rs 1,880 crore in April-May of the current year from Rs 1,131 crore in the same period of the previous fiscal.
